 Access to credit, plot size and cost inefficiency among 
 smallholder tobacco growers in Malawi 
 Gautam Hazarika a,*, Jeffrey AI wang b, 1 
 a 
 
 Department of Business Management, The University of Texas at Brownsville, 80 Fort Brown, Brownsville, TX 78520, USA 
 b Department of Farming-based and Applied Money flow, Virginia Tech, Blacksburg, VA 24060, USA 
 
 Received 8 May 2001; received in changed form 14 August 2002; accepted 15 August 2002 
 
 Abstract 
 Using data from the Malawi (money-related) Markets and Household Food Security Survey, this paper examines the effect of access 
 to credit from formal sources, and tobacco plot size, on cost inefficiency among Malawian smallholder tobacco growers. 
 Farm-specific cost inefficiency is guessed within the (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) of (random/including random data points) edge of something/unexplored area analysis. Access to credit is measured 
 as the sum of household members' (stated by the person doing a survey, etc.) credit limits at credit organisations, probably a truer measure of an (coming from the outside of something) 
 credit restriction than credit program participation or actual loan uptake. It is found that tobacco (producing crops/helping something grow) is significantly 
 less cost inefficient per area of land  on larger plots. While access to credit by itself has no (related to numbers) visible effect on cost 
 inefficiency, it reduces the gain in cost (wasting very little while working or producing something) from a larger plot size. 
