 types. Estate farms were viewed through the 1970's 
 and 1980's as the engines of (away from cities) growth, and the 
 former Banda country (ruled by one) used policies that favoured 
 the huge houses. These policies included exclusive marketing rights for high-value crops, other marketing policies that squeezed smallholders, and access to give money tod inputs and credit. While Malawian farming-based growth was fairly strong during the 1970's and 
 early 1980's, this growth was misleading since it did not 
 spread to the smallholder part/area. Smallholders now make up/be equal to around 70% of the Malawian population and about 90% of the country's poor. The middle-point area under (producing crops/helping something grow) by smallholders is a little 
 0.6 ha (World Bank, 1995). The high concentration 
 of poor in areas away from cities with small (areas of owned land) helps 
 permit the government's current focus on farming-based 
 (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) among smallholders as an engine of 
 poorness-reducing growth. 
 Recent policy changes designed to benefit smallholders have focused on two crops: combination maize varieties and burley tobacco. Malawian smallholders give/reserve some 70% of their land to maize, mostly local 
 varieties. Combination maize has not been widely adopted 
 for a few reasons, including the fact that the preferred hard combinations only became available in the early 
 1990's, the high relative cost of fertiliser, and lack of 
 credit. The new policy changes are expected to (help increase/show in a good way) uptake of combination maize and, this way, release land 
 for production of more money-making and mostly export 
 crops. Burley tobacco is the most likely candidate to 
 replace maize land. Burley tobacco is now 
 grown on some 150,000 ha of land and accounts for 
 at least 70% of Malawi's foreign exchange earnings 
 (about US$_$ (mUS$) 375 million, every year). The importance of this crop to the Malawian (process of people making, selling, and buying things) has 
 earned it the nickname 'green gold'. 
 Until (not very long ago), the Government of Malawi (helped increase/showed in a good way) 
 production of high-value cash crops like tobacco in the 
 estate part/area. Before 1990, under the Special Crops 
 Act of 1972, smallholders were prohibited from marketing tobacco. Smallholders' share of tobacco quotas 
 has, however, increased since 1990. Smallholder marketing quotas were first offered in the after-reform 
 time  to members of tobacco growers' clubs. An (middle-position) buyer program was introduced in 1993 that 
 allowed even non-members of tobacco clubs to sell 
 tobacco to registered traders. The number of smallholders producing tobacco has increased (a lot) 
 
 as a result of these policy changes (Zeller et al., 
 1997). 
 The smallholder burley tobacco program reflects a 
 big change in the Malawian farming-based development plan away from estate-led growth toward 
 a broad-based smallholder focus. Burley tobacco is 
 now seen as an engine that will provide useful things/valuable supplies to 
 cash-starved smallholders, will (combine different things together so they work as one unit) them into the 
 cash (process of people making, selling, and buying things), and allow flexibility and (trying new things out/testing ideas scientifically) in the (away from cities) part/area. The success of the program 
 depends upon the spread of burley tobacco production 
 to useful thing/valuable supply-poor farmers, the ability of smallholders 
 to (in a way that produces a lot with very little waste) produce high-quality tobacco products, 
 and complementaries between tobacco production and 
 other on-farm businesses/projects. 
 By examining the relationship between plot size 
 and cost inefficiency per area of land  in tobacco production, 
 this paper aims to discover whether the government's 
 promotion of smallholder tobacco (producing crops/helping something grow) has involved an equity-(wasting very little while working or producing something) trade-off. A negative relation between cost inefficiency and tobacco plot size 
 would suggest that the policy of de-focusing tobacco production in the estate part/area while encouraging it in smallholdings has helped equity at the 
 expense of (wasting very little while working or producing something). 
 This paper also examines the effect of smallholders' 
 access to credit upon their (wasting very little while working or producing something) in tobacco production. It is well known that the capital needed things 
 of tobacco farming are big. For example, Zeller 
 et al. (1997) find that input expenses per hectare 
 in Malawi are much greater for tobacco than for 
 maize or most other crops and that the cropping share 
 of tobacco in smallholdings is positively and significantly related to farmer access to credit. Because of this, 
 improving access to credit may be a necessary step 
 toward (accomplishing or gaining) more (existing all over a large area) burley tobacco production. However, besides encouraging the spread of 
 tobacco production, improved credit access may raise 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) in tobacco farming by enabling farmers to 
 better (instance of buying something for money) inputs in cost (making small) proportions 
 and to use/advantage of improvements in production technology. The relationship between credit availability and 
 money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something) in the Malawian smallholder 
 tobacco part/area has not (before that/before now) been completely 
 (examined something closely). 
 The paper's scientific plan, using data from 
 the Malawi (money-related) Markets and Household Food 
 Security Survey, consists of two steps, though in 
 
 G. Hazarika, J. A/wang I Farming-based Money flow 29 (2003) 99-109 
 
 keeping with recent econometric advances, the paper 
 later tries to combine the two steps into a single 
 step. First, farm-specific cost inefficiency per area of land  is 
 guessed within the (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) of (random/including random data points) edge of something/unexplored area 
 analysis (e.g. Parikh et al., 1995). Next, the guessed 
 cost inefficiency is related to farm and household 
 (features/ qualities/ traits) including tobacco plot size and access 
 to credit from formal sources. It is found that cost 
 inefficiency is negatively and significantly related 
 with tobacco land. Because of this, the government's focus 
 on smallholder led growth may in fact have involved 
 an equity-(wasting very little while working or producing something) trade-off. It is also found that 
 while access to credit by itself has no (meaningful numbers) effect on cost inefficiency, credit availability 
 has the counter-productive effect of reducing the gain 
 in cost (wasting very little while working or producing something) from an increase in tobacco land. 
 The rest of this paper is organised as follows. Section 2 presents a discussion of the relation 
 between credit access and cost (wasting very little while working or producing something) in farming. The section also discusses scientific issues in the 
 measurement of access to credit. Section 3 presents 
 the econometric model and discusses guess. The 
 data are described in Section 4, as are the scientific 
 results. Section 5 presents a summary of the findings 
 and the paper's end/end result. 
 
 2. Credit programs and cost (wasting very little while working or producing something) in 
 farm-related 
 Cost (wasting very little while working or producing something) results from both technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) and allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something). Technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 refers to a producer's ability to get the highest possible output from a amount of inputs. Think about/believe a unit 
 isoquant with capital and labour as the inputs. This 
 isoquant is the center  of the minimum capital-labour 
 combinations necessary to produce a unit of output. 
 Hence, production is technically (producing a lot with very little waste) along it. The 
 producer of a unit of output using a capital-labour 
 combination that lies above this isoquant is, therefore, 
 technically inefficient. 
 Allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) refers to a producer's ability to 
 (make as big as possible) (money made/good thing received) given technical (wasting very little while working or producing something). A producer 
 may be technically (producing a lot with very little waste) but allocatively inefficient. 
 For example, the producer in the previous/coming before paragraph 
 may put forward  a unit of output using a combination of 
 capital and labour that lies on the unit isoquant but that 
 is more expensive than a different combination of in- 
 
 101 
 
 puts on the isoquant. The cheapest input combination 
 would, of course, be the point of tangency between 
 an isocost line and the unit isoquant. Allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) also applies to the producer's ability to choose 
 the best level of output, or even the best output 
 mix. 
 Access to credit may raise allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) in 
 farming. For example, a farmer unable to get 
 market inputs in (good) enough amounts may substitute 
 non-market inputs such as the labour of family members. However, given the opportunity cost of family 
 labour, the farmer's input combination may be more 
 expensive than an different combination consisting of 
 more (bought) inputs and less family labour. Credit 
 may allow the farmer to use market and non-market 
 inputs in a cost (making small) combination. Credit may 
 also raise allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) by increasing a farmer's 
 ability to bear risk. For example, a farmer with access to credit may become willing to adopt riskier but 
 possibly more money-making technologies, or to plant a 
 more drought prone but higher value crop. 
 Credit access may also raise the farmer's level of 
 technical (wasting very little while working or producing something). For example, credit may enable a 
 farmer to put into use more capital-intensive methods of production, (in other words) to buy more machines, a market input. If the farmer (bought something for money) new machines clearly showing/including 
 improved technology, his level of technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 would rise. Further, to the extent that credit access is 
 related to the provision of technical help 
 (farming-based extension services) by credit organisations, farmers' technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) will increase. Note 
 that it is not necessary for a farmer to actually borrow 
 to benefit from credit access. For example, the mere 
 option of borrowing may lead a farmer to avoid such 
 risk reducing but (losing money) plans as (related to doing things to prevent trouble or injury) saving and the production of tougher but lower 
 value crops. Hence, a farmer with the option to borrow 
 may become willing to put the famous roll of bills 
 in his mattress to a more productive use on the farm. 
 Access to credit has generally been measured in two 
 ways in the books, namely, (divided into two) membership in credit programs, and actual loan uptake. Both 
 these measures may be no good for guessing the 
 true (proof that one thing definitely causes another) effect of credit access on money-based results (e.g. David and Meyer, 1980; Feder et al., 1990; 
 Zeller et al., 1996). First, since credit program participation and loan uptake are (something you choose to do, but is not required), the measures 
 are possibly endogenous with results such as 
 
 102 
 
 G. Hazarika, J. Alwang!Agricultural Money flow 29 (2003) 99-109 
 
 working well and income. A farmer who gets/helps of loans 
 from a credit (service business/government unit/power/functioning) may be found to be more productive, but it may not be decided that loans lead 
 to higher working well since it is reasonable that farmers 
 with more desire and ability are likelier to search for 
 loans. Such qualities, being unseen, are unlikely to 
 be controlled for in a moving backward relating farming-based 
 working well to farmer loan uptake, with the result that 
 the moving backward's error term, consisting partially of unseen farmer qualities, will be related to loan uptake. Bias in the OLS guess of the effect of farmer 
 loan uptake on farming-based working well is, therefore, 
 likely. 
 Even if the possible endogeneity of actual loan uptake were dealt with, (problems, delays, etc.) with this measure of 
 credit access would continue. For example, built into 
 it is the wrong idea (you think is true) that people with 
 no loan uptake are without access to credit. However, 
 this would only be true if they were denied loans. 
 More generally, actual loan uptake would be an correct measure of credit access only if credit limits 
 were (existing everywhere) binding, (in other words) if everyone's loan uptake 
 were equal to her credit limit. In reality, people often do not fully exercise their option to borrow. 
 In fact, as discussed earlier, an individual who does 
 not at all exercise the option to borrow may yet benefit from that option, for example, by feeling secure 
 enough to adopt possibly more money-making but riskier 
 plans. 
 Next, membership in a credit program often gives/discusses benefits unrelated to credit access such as reading and writing ability classes and business training. For example, members of the Malawi (away from cities) Finance Company's (MRFC) 
 credit program are given farming-based extension services. These secondary benefits of credit program participation probably confuse the true (proof that one thing definitely causes another) 
 effect of access to credit. Finally, mere membership 
 in a credit program may not (promise that something will definitely happen or that something will definitely work as described) ready access 
 to credit. In fact, many group-based credit programs 
 say that only half of a group's members may receive credit at any time. Even credit programs denying this rule rarely provide their members with 
 certain access to credit. 
 Hence, Diagne ( 1998) and Diagne and Zeller (200 I) 
 argue that the credit limit, the maximum amount that 
 may be borrowed as (stated by the person doing a survey, etc.) by survey people (who were part of a study, etc.), is a better measure of credit access. The authors reason that unlike credit program participation 
 
 or actual loan uptake, which are related to demand for 
 credit, the credit limit, reflecting mainly supply-side 
 factors such as the availability of credit programs and 
 the money supplies of lenders, is a truer measure of 
 an (coming from the outside of something) credit restriction. So, this paper measures a tobacco producing household's access to credit 
 by the sum of the credit limits of its members at credit 
 organisations. 
 To be sure, this (compared to other things) novel measure of credit 
 access is not clearly (coming from the outside of something) (uncorrelated 
 with unseen borrower (features/ qualities/ traits)). For example, Diagne (1998) agrees that the maximum amount 
 that lenders are willing to lend will mirror their test of the chance of default and other borrower 
 (features/ qualities/ traits). Hence, an (producing a lot with very little waste) tobacco farmer may 
 have a higher self-tested credit limit than an inefficient one. The OLS guessed effect of credit access 
 on cost inefficiency might, this way, be (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) downward. 
 On the other hand, since an goal of non-profit 
 agro-(money-related) institutions in LDCs may be the reduction of money-based inefficiency, more inefficient farmers may be made/gave/given greater help. The OLS guessed effect of credit access on cost inefficiency 
 might, as a result, even be (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) upward. Anyway, it is reasonable that the credit limit measure of 
 access to credit is (compared to other things) more (coming from the outside of something) than actual loan uptake or (divided into two) membership in credit 
 programs, which are carefully planned acts on the part of borrowers and, therefore, probably related to 
 their unseen attributes. 
 
