 The above two-stage method, consisting of ML guess of a (random/including random data points) cost edge of something/unexplored area followed by OLS 
 guess of an equation relating (described the future) cost inefficiency to the possible (things that decide other things) of cost inefficiency, has lately been criticised. For one, a moving backward 
 model of (described the future) inefficiency effects in Stage 2 argues with the idea (you think is true) in Stage 1 of identically distributed inefficiency effects (Battese and Coelli, 1995). 
 Hence, the twin steps are (using other choices) combined into a 
 single step according the model by Battese and Coelli 
 (1995). It is continued to be assumed that V;, random 
