 words, the mean of the cost inefficiency effect is assumed to be a function of (numbers that change/things that change) Z;, taken in the 
 scientific guess, to be identical to the move backwardors 
 in (5). This (detailed description of exactly what is required) permits the coefficients e to 
 be guessed together with the coefficients of the cost 
 edge of something/unexplored area (1). 
 
 4. The data and scientific results 
 Data for the study are drawn from the Malawi (money-related) Markets and Household Food Security Survey 
 conducted both/together in 1995 by the International Food 
 Policy Research Institute (IFPRI) and the Department 
 of (away from cities) Development (DRP) of the Bunda College 
 of Farming of the University of Malawi. A total 
 of 404 (away from cities) families in 45 villages in five districts 
 of Malawi were surveyed. The yearlong survey (from 
 February to December) consisted of three rounds. The 
 scientific analyses are managed and did/done upon data from the 
 second round of the survey, since only it contained 
 the necessary described/explained tobacco production data. While 
 rarely in household surveys is labour input disaggregated by crop, these data permit the (putting a value on something) of labour 
 used/paid in tobacco (producing crops/helping something grow) alone towards calculation of the cost per area of land  of tobacco production. 
 There are four main credit and savings programs now operating in Malawi: the Malawi 
 (away from cities) Finance Company (MRFC), Promotion of 
 Micro-Businesses/projects for (away from cities) Women (PMERW), the 
 Malawi Mudzi Fund (MMF), and the Malawi Union 
 
 104 
 
 G. Hazarika, J. A/wang/Agricultural Money flow 29 (2003) 99-109 
 
 of Savings and Credit Co-operatives (MUSCCO). 
 The first three programs are based on the ways of thinking/basic truths/rules 
 of group lending, while MUSCCO is an individual membership based union organisation. MRFC 
 and MUSCCO provide seasonal farming-based credit, 
 mostly for tobacco and maize, though the former does 
 not serve families with less than half a hectare of 
 land. PMERW and MMF, operating in only a few 
 districts, (focus on doing one thing very well) in credit for off-farm businesses/projects. 
 There are, also, many small credit programs run by NGOs and international government 
 organisations. 
 The above 404 (away from cities) families do not make up/be equal to a 
 random sample. Since it was necessary to include (good) enough numbers of credit program people (who were part of a study, etc.) in the 
 survey, the low participation rate in credit programs 
 in Malawi made random sampling silly/not doable. Because of this, 
 the surveyors chose to/chosen to layered random sampling. 
 The 4700 (away from cities) families listed in the 45 villages covered by the Malawi village (official count of everyone who lives in a country, city, etc.)  were divided into three layers: a layer consisting of current 
 people (who were part of a study, etc.) in the above four credit programs, a layer consisting of past people (who were part of a study, etc.) (mostly in a failed 
 government credit program), and a layer consisting 
 of families that had never participated in a credit 
 program. A random sample was chosen from each 
 layer such that about half of the final sample of 404 
 families consisted of current credit program people (who were part of a study, etc.), with past people (who were part of a study, etc.) and non-people (who were part of a study, etc.) 
 making up about equal parts of/amounts of the rest. So, the survey over samples current credit 
 program people (who were part of a study, etc.). The scientific guess incorporates sampling weights in an attempt to account for 
 this over sampling. 
 In each round of the Malawi (money-related) Markets and 
 Household Food Security Survey, people who responded over 17 
 years old were asked about the maximum amount 
 they might possibly have borrowed during the period of recall. A household's access to credit from formal sources may, this way, be calculated as the sum of the 
 credit limits of its members at credit organisations. 
 The cost per area of land  of tobacco production is measured 
 as the sum of the costs of seed, fertiliser, bug-killer, and 
 labour input, and the costs of moving inputs to the 
 farm and moving the crop to market. The inputs 
 whose log prices are included in the (detailed description of exactly what is required) of 
 the (random/including random data points) cost function (1), are: labour, seed, fertiliser, and bug-killer. Farm and household characteris- 
 
 muscle twitches/weird behaviors with reasonable holding upon cost inefficiency, the 
 (numbers that change/things that change) Xi in (4) and (5), include the value of farm 
 valuable things, farm size, household size, the average age of 
 12-year-old or older family members, the proportion 
 of family members (old/allowed to get old/got older) 12 and above able to read and 
 write Chichewa, the proportion able to read and write 
 English, and the proportions with the educational (written proof of something): First (or most important) School Leaving Certificate (Grade 
 8), Junior Certificate (Grade 10), and M.S.C.E. certificate (Grade 12). (connected/related) data were available for 
 70 tobacco helping grow families. However, it was 
 discovered that tobacco land (in a mistaken way) went beyond 
 farm size in three of these families, no doubt, due 
 to coding error. The three families were dropped, 
 producing/giving up a final sample of 67 families. Table 1 
 presents the (unweighted) sample means and standard 
 mistakes of the (numbers that change/things that change). 
 Table 2 presents weighted maximum-chance 3 guesses of the (random/including random data points) cost edge of something/unexplored area. The cost per 
 area of land  of producing tobacco increases (a lot) in 
 the value of output per area of land, in the hourly wage, in the 
 price per kilogram of tobacco seed, and in the price 
 per kilogram of fertiliser. Cost, however, appears to 
 decrease in the cost per kilogram of bug-killer. 
