 (5). It is assumed that tobacco land is an (coming from the outside of something) move backwardor, or that farmers first set apart land between tobacco and other crops and only (after that) 
 make their tobacco inputs use decisions. This 
 is a reasonable idea (you think is true) in the Malawian big picture. 
 The average cropping share of tobacco in Malawian 
 smallholdings is only about 2% (Diagne and Zeller, 
 2001). Diagne and Zeller (2001) argue that this 
