 does not by itself significantly affect cost inefficiency. 
 However, the sign of the guessed coefficient of the 
 interaction between tobacco land and credit access, 
 together with the (meaningful numbers) of this (number or thing that changes), hints that the helpful effect of a larger tobacco plot size on cost inefficiency is worn-away by access 
 to credit. Credit in Malawi is often paid in the 
 form of farming-based inputs like fertiliser. The fertiliser 
 packages are standardised for only a small number of 
 plot sizes with the result that a farmer may be lent 
 an too much/too many amount of fertiliser (Diagne and Zeller, 
 2001). To the extent that a household's credit limit is 
 related to its actual loan uptake, 4 this type of loan 
 payment may add/give to the above negative effect of the credit limit upon the gain in cost (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 from a larger tobacco plot size. In other words, the 
 (making up for something/paying for something) over-use of inputs may reduce with increased tobacco land, but a (happening together) increase 
 in access to credit may add/give to toughness in 
 farmers' too much/too many input application per tobacco area of land. 
 There are some other findings of interest. For 
 example, controlling for tobacco land, total farm 
 land and cost inefficiency in tobacco production are 
 positively related. Holding tobacco land constant, 
 larger farms naturally have more land under crops 
 
 other than tobacco, such as maize, the major Malawian 
 food crop. To the extent that these crops require large 
 applications of market inputs like fertiliser, 5 that farmers are useful thing/valuable supply strapped, and that market inputs are in 
 (compared to other things) short supply, the amounts per area of land  of such 
 inputs applied to tobacco may be inversely related to 
 land under other crops. Allocative inefficiency in 
 input application may result. For example, the reduced 
 use of market inputs in tobacco may be went with 
 by a (making up for something/paying for something) over-application of non-market inputs such as household labour. Cost inefficiency per 
 area of land  may as a result rise. It is important/famous in this connection that the guesses in Table 3 are a strong sign of a 
 habit/desire toward the over-use of family labour on tobacco plots, in that cost inefficiency per area of land  increases 
 in the number of household members. (in almost the same way), an increase in the average age of household members older 
