 The above findings may be contrasted with the results from two other studies relating (wasting very little while working or producing something) in farming-based production, measured within the (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) 
 of (random/including random data points) edge of something/unexplored area analysis, to credit availability and 
 plot size. Parikh et al. (1995) examine the (things that decide other things) 
 of cost inefficiency, including credit availability and 
 farm size, in Pakistani farming. Credit availability 
 is defined as actual loan uptake per farm area of land. The 
 authors find that farmers with greater loan uptake are 
 less cost inefficient. However, since this measure of 
 credit access is possibly endogenous as discussed, 
 the above finding may not be relied upon. The authors 
 also find that cost inefficiency increases in farm size. 
