 single crop. Therefore, the finding that Malawian tobacco (producing crops/helping something grow) is less cost inefficient in larger plots 
 may not be directly compared with the above finding 
 that cost inefficiency in Pakistani farming increases 
 in holding size. 
 Ali and Flinn (1989) examine (money made/good thing received), not cost, 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) among basmati rice producers in the Punjab area of control/area of land of Pakistan. Still, there are (things that are almost the same as other things) 
 between the ideas of cost (wasting very little while working or producing something) and profit 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) in that both arise from technical as well 
 as allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something). Farmers, in this study, were 
 asked if a lack of credit slowed their (instance of buying something for money) of 
 fertiliser. Because of this, a (divided into two) indicator of credit 
 non-availability measures access to credit. Credit 
 non-availability was positively and significantly related to (make money/get something good) inefficiency. Since a farmer referring to credit 
 non-availability is one who has tried to borrow, 
 this measure of credit access is, like actual loan uptake, possibly endogenous. The authors also find 
 that profit inefficiency increases in farm size, though 
 not significantly so. 
 
 5. End/end result 
 The promotion of tobacco (producing crops/helping something grow) is a key part of the Malawian plan of smallholder-led 
 growth. Given the big capital needed things of 
 tobacco farming, improving farmers' access to credit 
 may be necessary toward (accomplishing or gaining) more (existing all over a large area) 
 burley tobacco production. In fact, there is (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) 
 of positive relationship between access to credit and 
 the cropping share of tobacco in smallholdings (Zeller 
 et al., 1997). However, this paper finds no (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) of 
 a positive relation between access to credit from formal sources and (wasting very little while working or producing something) in tobacco farming. So, 
 improving farmers' access to credit in Malawi will 
 likely (help increase/show in a good way) tobacco (producing crops/helping something grow) only along the long/big margin. 
 Unlike most analyses of the effects of credit, this 
 paper measures household access to credit from formal sources as the sum of members' (stated by the person doing a survey, etc.) 
 credit limits at credit organisations. It has (before that/before now) 
 been argued that the credit limit is a truer measure 
 of an (coming from the outside of something) credit restriction since it reflects 
 mostly supply-side factors such as the availability of 
 credit programs and the money supplies of lenders 
 (Diagne, 1998; Diagne and Zeller, 2001). 
 
 The paper also finds that tobacco (producing crops/helping something grow) is less 
 cost inefficient on larger plots. This may be taken 
 as a strong sign of an equity-(wasting very little while working or producing something) trade-off in the 
 Malawian tobacco part/area. The finding hints that 
 the Government of Malawi's policy of encouraging tobacco production by smallholders instead of supporting the previous control of the tobacco huge houses, 
 has led to (lowering in number/getting worse) cost (wasting very little while working or producing something) in the production of 
 this premier cash crop, even if it has (helped increase/showed in a good way) equity 
 in the (away from cities) (process of people making, selling, and buying things). It also hints that increasing 
 the cropping share of tobacco in smallholdings from 
 its current low levels will tend to raise the money-based 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) of tobacco production. 
 The paper also uncovers (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) that access to 
 credit retards the gain in cost (wasting very little while working or producing something) from an increase in tobacco land. This hints that the methods of credit payment in (away from cities) Malawi are broken. 
 In fact, broken credit payment (machines/methods/ways) may 
 partially explain why access to credit by itself, (even though there is the existence of) 
 its possible benefits, has no (related to numbers) visible 
 effect on cost inefficiency. 
 Our findings have two broad policy effects/results/suggestions. 
 As argued, an increase in the cropping share of tobacco in smallholdings may reduce cost inefficiency 
 in the production of this crop. Therefore, policies that 
 rid farmers of their habit/desire to set apart most of 
 their (areas of owned land) to maize may raise (wasting very little while working or producing something) in tobacco production. Such policies may include efforts to 
 improve the functioning of (away from cities) maize markets so as 
 to reduce the need for independence in maize. Next, 
 credit payment (machines/methods/ways) in Malawi may require a degree of reform. It should be secured/made sure of that 
 farmers are not lent too much/too many amounts of expensive inputs. Tobacco is an very important cash crop to 
 the Malawian (process of people making, selling, and buying things) and it is a good idea that the 
 Government of Malawi energetically chase after policies to 
 raise money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something) in its production. 
 
